And the first day, I didn't know if I would be seated or not.

607
01:13:35,000 --> 01:13:40,000
Until 15 minutes before I was seated.

608
01:13:40,000 --> 01:13:51,000
When Marion Wright came back on the outside, where I was on the south side of the Capitol, and told me Robert, they have decided to seat you.

609
01:13:51,000 --> 01:14:04,000
And then when I went in, again, because of my experience at Michigan State and Western Michigan University,

610
01:14:04,000 --> 01:14:12,000
the being one black among 121 white, that did not intimidate me at all.

611
01:14:12,000 --> 01:14:15,000
Because I knew what I knew.

612
01:14:15,000 --> 01:14:26,000
And one thing that I knew, what I was going to zero in on, was what I was an expert in, and that was education.

613
01:14:26,000 --> 01:14:34,000
And I knew no one there knew as much about education as I did.

614
01:14:34,000 --> 01:14:37,000
But you had to wait a while.

615
01:14:37,000 --> 01:14:41,000
I think for about eight years, you were the only black in the legislature.

616
01:14:41,000 --> 01:14:55,000
Yes, I was on the black and the legislation when I went in about first day, the regulations of the House walls, you know, you had districts.

617
01:14:55,000 --> 01:15:06,000
And the senior person in that district would choose the seating far, the rest of the members, and here's a her district.

618
01:15:06,000 --> 01:15:17,000
So on this side, where I'm sitting now, that's the door where you come in, right in front of me. That's the door.

619
01:15:17,000 --> 01:15:25,000
All right. And this first line was two seats. All right.

620
01:15:25,000 --> 01:15:30,000
And then I'll come between us, and that's three seats.

621
01:15:30,000 --> 01:15:41,000
So the old gentleman that was the senior of my delegation, he chose this seat for me. This seat for me.

622
01:15:41,000 --> 01:15:51,000
And his seat is crossed our from me. Then the other member from my other district, his seat across the aisle from me.

623
01:15:51,000 --> 01:16:01,000
All right. Now, the vacant seat is far the speaker of the house. When able to speak of the house is not preside.

624
01:16:01,000 --> 01:16:09,000
But the speaker of the house had him another seat moved to the back of the Capitol.

625
01:16:09,000 --> 01:16:15,000
And now that wouldn't burn him. That's John, John. Okay. That's John, John, John, John.

626
01:16:15,000 --> 01:16:30,000
And so you were asked, I said, if that seat, Bob, myself, but out of the point for eight years, the folks from one final set beside me.

627
01:16:30,000 --> 01:16:40,000
Tell us a little bit about those early, well, the first and second terms. Were you excluded from everything?

628
01:16:40,000 --> 01:16:47,000
You were determined that you were going to be a good legislator. How did that work out with all of this?

629
01:16:47,000 --> 01:16:59,000
Well, first of all, I couldn't get the floor to house. If I stand for recognition, somebody to make a motion.

630
01:16:59,000 --> 01:17:09,000
I'm already standing. These poses, you know, Robert Roos of order, but he'd recognize somebody else to cut me out. And I couldn't get the floor.

631
01:17:09,000 --> 01:17:18,000
So one night, this is my first time. I walked out and Bill Monter, you know, Bill Monter, yes.

632
01:17:18,000 --> 01:17:27,000
Very, very outrageous course. Yes. And Bertilemmon, they came out. I had cleaned my desk. I had everything.

633
01:17:27,000 --> 01:17:37,000
And they came out and coming after me and pushed them out of my way. And I reached for my door.

634
01:17:37,000 --> 01:17:44,000
And by that time Bill Monter said, okay, go ahead and do it. You're doing what they want you to do.

635
01:17:44,000 --> 01:17:53,000
You were just ready to walk out. I was ready to walk out. Walk out. And when Bill Monter said, you're doing what they want you to do.

636
01:17:53,000 --> 01:18:00,000
And when he said that, I dropped my hand and walked back in. And when I walked back in on the floor of the house,

637
01:18:00,000 --> 01:18:10,000
man, they was having a hooray. They was whoo-fisland, they was clapping and they was doing everything.

638
01:18:10,000 --> 01:18:17,000
And when I walked back in, they got just a cry.

639
01:18:17,000 --> 01:18:27,000
That's right. But what I did when I first went to the legislature, you know, I had the school and that helped me.

640
01:18:27,000 --> 01:18:34,000
You know, I prepared myself for what legislation was coming up. And what I was going to do,

641
01:18:34,000 --> 01:18:42,000
sometimes I did just like a dinner at Michigan State, a Western Michigan, a Sydney burning midnight hour.

642
01:18:42,000 --> 01:18:51,000
So I would be prepared. And if they did agree with me, they knew that they couldn't share his wrong.

643
01:18:51,000 --> 01:18:52,000
They were at the news when I was talking about it.

644
01:18:52,000 --> 01:19:01,000
How long was it before somebody asked you for your vote?

645
01:19:01,000 --> 01:19:04,000
Maybe about eight years. Really? Maybe about eight years?

646
01:19:04,000 --> 01:19:18,000
That's that long. Yes, sir. And after eight years, we got the group in Jackson elected.

647
01:19:18,000 --> 01:19:19,000
Red Bay.

648
01:19:19,000 --> 01:19:23,000
Group of Black electors are basically enjoying you.

649
01:19:23,000 --> 01:19:25,000
In the state legislation?

650
01:19:25,000 --> 01:19:33,000
Yes, sir. You got three from Jackson elected. They did redistricted and got them re-elected.

651
01:19:33,000 --> 01:19:46,000
But after some of those issues, you know, I would speak out on them, some of the technical issues,

652
01:19:46,000 --> 01:20:02,000
and I could present myself on them. And some of those same elderly white gentlemen that, you know, were the pose to me being seated.

653
01:20:02,000 --> 01:20:10,000
Now, some folks say I was being an unketone for doing it. But sometimes they would know what's going on.

654
01:20:10,000 --> 01:20:16,000
And when time came to vote, they'd be jumping up trying to get my teaching.

655
01:20:16,000 --> 01:20:24,000
And if he's supposed to vote I, I'd tell him I, if he's supposed to vote no, I'd point to my nostrils.

656
01:20:24,000 --> 01:20:27,000
These are your younger colleagues in the Cappuella.

657
01:20:27,000 --> 01:20:32,000
Well, now these are some of the older, older white gentlemen.

658
01:20:32,000 --> 01:20:35,000
I see. So that's a big change.

659
01:20:35,000 --> 01:20:44,000
They're older white gentlemen. That's my summer. Black folk was telling me that, you know, I've been an unketone.

660
01:20:44,000 --> 01:20:50,000
But I didn't do them like they did me.

661
01:20:50,000 --> 01:20:58,000
In particular, I lived somebody come up like the gentleman from Vicksburg, with real sharp.

662
01:20:58,000 --> 01:21:05,000
The gentleman from the Luxe, real sharp, gentleman from Greenville, real sharp.

663
01:21:05,000 --> 01:21:12,000
And if they had something and they didn't know, they looked to me for me to direct them.

664
01:21:12,000 --> 01:21:19,000
But the true feels are never directed one in the wrong manner.

665
01:21:19,000 --> 01:21:30,000
And the first seatmate that I had, his white seatmate, then when it come up, he'd ask me how to vote the vote.

666
01:21:30,000 --> 01:21:34,000
If he's supposed to vote no, I'd say he's supposed to vote no.

667
01:21:34,000 --> 01:21:39,000
And then finally he asked me, he said, I want to ask you one thing.

668
01:21:39,000 --> 01:21:46,000
What you trying to do, get me defeated. That's a what you're talking about.

669
01:21:46,000 --> 01:22:00,000
You tell me to vote one way and you vote another. I said, hey, old man, I'm trying to tell you how to vote, how your vote back home won't you to vote.

670
01:22:00,000 --> 01:22:10,000
Well, about 10 years after you were first elected, you were appointed chairman of the House Education Committee.

671
01:22:10,000 --> 01:22:17,000
How did that happen? I mean, here nobody would talk to you and now you're in the chair of an important committee.

672
01:22:17,000 --> 01:22:20,000
Tell us how, what has happened before that could happen.

673
01:22:20,000 --> 01:22:28,000
All right, that is very interesting. That is very interesting.

674
01:22:28,000 --> 01:22:37,000
When CB Betten Newman was running far, Speaker Pro Tem, ought to fill in far,

675
01:22:37,000 --> 01:22:44,000
when John Junkin got sick, John Junkin was the speaker.

676
01:22:44,000 --> 01:22:51,000
So, Betten Newman met me on the first floor of the Capitol.

677
01:22:51,000 --> 01:23:02,000
I happened following a group, a so-called Libras, my good friend, but they'd all get good appointments and I'd wind up with nothing.

678
01:23:02,000 --> 01:23:17,000
So, Betten Newman asked me and met me on the first floor and he said, I need one more signal to and I will have a majority.

679
01:23:17,000 --> 01:23:27,000
And can I get you to sign it? I said, let me see it and I looked at it and I saw he needed one more.

680
01:23:27,000 --> 01:23:37,000
And I thought about, I was thinking about. All these years, I'm not following my other boys that I've been following and they get it burned and I don't get nothing.

681
01:23:37,000 --> 01:23:51,000
I'm going to look out for myself. So, I saw that I signed it and when I signed it, he dropped to one knee and he said,

682
01:23:51,000 --> 01:23:58,000
who, he dropped to one knee and he kissed that pin that I signed it with.

683
01:23:58,000 --> 01:24:07,000
And he said, who ever thought that white may be on his knee to a nigger?

684
01:24:07,000 --> 01:24:17,000
And I said, let's speak, you Peckaborch, you have to do a lot more of that from Black folks and the future.

685
01:24:17,000 --> 01:24:19,000
And what about you, what was the sacred day?

686
01:24:19,000 --> 01:24:26,000
Betten Newman, Betten Newman. And I signed that.

687
01:24:26,000 --> 01:24:37,000
Then, Betten I became, well, we could communicate. We could communicate to each other, with each other.

688
01:24:37,000 --> 01:24:45,000
And then, after Johnkins died, Betten became Speaker.

689
01:24:45,000 --> 01:24:55,000
I wanted Betten to appoint me as Chairman of Wildlife and Fisheries. He said, no, I got something else for you, better than that.

690
01:24:55,000 --> 01:25:00,000
So, he appointed me Vice Chairman of Education.

691
01:25:01,000 --> 01:25:14,000
All right. President Carter was elected. And George Rogers, who was the child person, he was appointed to President Carter's cabinet.

692
01:25:14,000 --> 01:25:23,000
All right, Aaron Henry was convening the State NAACP Convention in Vicksburg.

693
01:25:23,000 --> 01:25:29,000
And that's in Betten Newman District. He lived in the Queen of County. But his district was Vicksburg.

694
01:25:30,000 --> 01:25:40,000
So, I went, Aaron invited me to be the keynote speaker. And I spoke and I told Black folks,

695
01:25:40,000 --> 01:25:49,000
as time for you to get up and do something for yourself, don't sit around and wait for White folks to be giving you a hand up.

696
01:25:49,000 --> 01:25:51,000
Get up and do something for yourself.

697
01:25:52,000 --> 01:26:03,000
Lord, behold, the next day in the paper and bold headlight, potential Negro chair gives Black Power Speak.

698
01:26:05,000 --> 01:26:14,000
So, I just knew it was all over. So, about 10 days, Betten Newman sent for me to come to his office.

699
01:26:14,000 --> 01:26:21,000
So, when I went to his office, he had three boxes, about that high, sitting on his desk.

700
01:26:21,000 --> 01:26:31,000
And he opened one of the boxes and pulled one of the papers out and said, take that look at that.

701
01:26:31,000 --> 01:26:35,000
I want you to see that. I looked at it.

702
01:26:35,000 --> 01:26:42,000
I said, well, yes, I'm a speaker. I did. I gave the speech. I said it.

703
01:26:42,000 --> 01:26:49,000
He said, what I call you in here to tell you that there ain't no vacancy yet.

704
01:26:49,000 --> 01:26:56,000
But when there is a vacancy, I will approach you.

705
01:26:56,000 --> 01:27:10,000
And that really changed my attitude towards him, with him having the pride to override all those spoken as district and to do that.

706
01:27:11,000 --> 01:27:21,000
That was something that I think is for and that you did what you had to do to become chair of the Education Committee.

707
01:27:21,000 --> 01:27:30,000
And as a result of that, you were responsible for, along with others, for pushing through one of the most important pieces of legislation.

708
01:27:31,000 --> 01:27:36,000
I think a long, long time. And that was the Education Reform Act.

709
01:27:36,000 --> 01:27:47,000
Tell us about William Witter, I think, with Governor Ben. Tell us about that debate and what the act does for a bid for the state.

710
01:27:47,000 --> 01:27:59,000
All right. As we get into that, before that, a white lawyer from Lexington had to call me and tell me what's coming up on the floor and part of it.

711
01:28:00,000 --> 01:28:05,000
I was trying to get on the inside.

712
01:28:05,000 --> 01:28:11,000
I went to the legislature as an education legislator.

713
01:28:11,000 --> 01:28:21,000
And I had been pushing for education, progressive education, first bail introduced when I went to Dr. King's field in Atlanta.

714
01:28:21,000 --> 01:28:24,000
They called a bail up and killed at that date.

715
01:28:25,000 --> 01:28:33,000
All right. Then after Governor William Witter became governor, which was great.

716
01:28:33,000 --> 01:28:47,000
And then he, we worked out a bill with him and we put together a bill, education reform, we call it.

717
01:28:48,000 --> 01:28:55,000
And I would make sure that I would get my bills out first.

718
01:28:55,000 --> 01:29:02,000
You know, the bills come out and be on the calendar, calling to how they come out of the committee.

719
01:29:02,000 --> 01:29:13,000
But the Rouge Committee had the authority at that time to rearrange the bill, the calendar, and they could kick the bill to the Hill of the Committee.

720
01:29:13,000 --> 01:29:19,000
So I met an 82 meeting before we went into the session.

721
01:29:19,000 --> 01:29:24,000
And we got our bill out the first week in the session.

722
01:29:24,000 --> 01:29:31,000
All right. Then they constantly kicked the bill back to the Hill of the Cal.

723
01:29:31,000 --> 01:29:34,000
Kick it back to the Hill of the Cal.

724
01:29:34,000 --> 01:29:42,000
So getting near the end of the session, I got my vice chairman, who was a white person.

725
01:29:42,000 --> 01:29:52,000
And another individual who was a very conservative, but he's a white person, but he's a poser.

726
01:29:52,000 --> 01:29:55,000
And we went to the Speaker's office.

727
01:29:55,000 --> 01:30:10,000
I said, Ms. Speaker, I can't be your office to let you know that I'm going to call this bill, I gave a number to bill, up for a meeting consideration.

728
01:30:10,000 --> 01:30:14,000
He says, I hope you wouldn't do that.

729
01:30:14,000 --> 01:30:20,000
I said, well, the time has arrived, Ms. Speaker, for us to do that.

730
01:30:20,000 --> 01:30:24,000
And he said, some of these boys can't stand the heat.

731
01:30:24,000 --> 01:30:30,000
I said, Mr. Speaker, they ain't supposed to be no boys on the floor of the house.

732
01:30:30,000 --> 01:30:33,000
If there's any boys, they're supposed to go home.

733
01:30:34,000 --> 01:30:40,000
And I shook his hand and I said, I'm going to make the motion.

734
01:30:40,000 --> 01:30:42,000
He says, I'm not going to recognize you.

735
01:30:42,000 --> 01:30:43,000
I said, thank you.

736
01:30:43,000 --> 01:30:46,000
Then my vice chairman said the same thing.

737
01:30:46,000 --> 01:30:52,000
He said, Mr. Speaker, if you don't recognize him, I'm going to make the motion.

738
01:30:52,000 --> 01:30:59,000
So then we went to the Florida House and we began to, you know, convene.

739
01:30:59,000 --> 01:31:03,000
At the proper time I stood it, made the motion.

740
01:31:03,000 --> 01:31:08,000
What does the gentleman from home wish to be recognized for?

741
01:31:08,000 --> 01:31:16,000
Ms. Speaker, the call house bill, such as such a number, up to the top of the calendar for a meeting consideration, rapped together.

742
01:31:16,000 --> 01:31:20,000
You're out of order, you're not recognized.

743
01:31:20,000 --> 01:31:26,000
And then my vice chairman did the same thing.

744
01:31:26,000 --> 01:31:29,000
All right, and he did the same thing to him.

745
01:31:29,000 --> 01:31:36,000
All right, then the house got in search of uproar until they just had to a join.

746
01:31:36,000 --> 01:31:48,000
But during that same time, I was seen letters that one of my colleagues from Cleveland, Mississippi, had brought white colleague,

747
01:31:48,000 --> 01:31:53,000
what we're going to do to your wife and your family if you vote for that bill.

748
01:31:53,000 --> 01:32:03,000
I had seen a letter from one of my colleagues in Yazoo City, what we're going to do to your wife and family.

749
01:32:03,000 --> 01:32:13,000
I had seen a letter from one of my colleagues out in East West Jackson, in Clinton.

750
01:32:13,000 --> 01:32:16,000
That's why he's really from Clinton.

751
01:32:16,000 --> 01:32:19,000
That's what we're going to do to your wife and family.

752
01:32:19,000 --> 01:32:21,000
Now who was writing these letters?

753
01:32:21,000 --> 01:32:24,000
And these were letters to people who were supporting the education?

754
01:32:24,000 --> 01:32:29,000
Let us to people on my committee who were supporting me.

755
01:32:29,000 --> 01:32:38,000
These would be from people back in their home telling them what they're going to do to their family.

756
01:32:38,000 --> 01:32:41,000
But they didn't have no names on them.

757
01:32:41,000 --> 01:32:51,000
So then at the end of that session, I went to Governor William Wattas office.

758
01:32:51,000 --> 01:33:07,000
I said, Governor Wattas, I said, if we can't get some kind of support, I don't know if I can keep on putting my members through this blood bath again.

759
01:33:08,000 --> 01:33:10,000
And he said, what we need to do.

760
01:33:10,000 --> 01:33:13,000
I said, you need to take it to the people.

761
01:33:13,000 --> 01:33:17,000
I said, you need to take it to some of the old line organizations.

762
01:33:17,000 --> 01:33:21,000
Like the Mississippi Southern Baptist, like the Farm Bureau.

763
01:33:21,000 --> 01:33:25,000
And we had that conversation.

764
01:33:25,000 --> 01:33:29,000
And that was the only conversation me and him had.

765
01:33:29,000 --> 01:33:34,000
So when I was a campaigner for Congress, I laid it to.

766
01:33:34,000 --> 01:33:38,000
And I jumped it to go to his meeting.

767
01:33:38,000 --> 01:33:43,000
He was having a Greenville at the Convention and Visitors Bureau.

768
01:33:43,000 --> 01:33:48,000
But I couldn't get within three blocks of their Convention Center.

769
01:33:48,000 --> 01:33:51,000
It was so many folks there.

770
01:33:51,000 --> 01:33:58,000
So after he had those meetings, he summoned six legislators.

771
01:33:58,000 --> 01:34:01,000
Three members of the House.

772
01:34:01,000 --> 01:34:04,000
And three members of the Senate.

773
01:34:04,000 --> 01:34:06,000
Two, they're in the mansion.

774
01:34:06,000 --> 01:34:08,000
Governor's Mansion.

775
01:34:08,000 --> 01:34:17,000
And he says, I'm not calling your here to ask your if I should call a space association.

776
01:34:17,000 --> 01:34:24,000
He said, but I'm calling your here to let your know I'm going to have a press conference.

777
01:34:24,000 --> 01:34:26,000
I'm going to get a date.

778
01:34:26,000 --> 01:34:34,000
And at that time, I will announce if I will call a space association or not.

779
01:34:34,000 --> 01:34:37,000
So that was the essence of that meeting.

780
01:34:37,000 --> 01:34:39,000
So shut up.

781
01:34:39,000 --> 01:34:44,000
Governor Wetter called the space association.

782
01:34:44,000 --> 01:34:46,000
All right.

783
01:34:46,000 --> 01:34:51,000
The speaker, Mr. Speaker.

784
01:34:51,000 --> 01:35:00,000
He summoned the same three legislators, members of the House to the Lieutenant Governor's Office.

785
01:35:00,000 --> 01:35:09,000
And the Lieutenant Governor summoned the same three members of the Senate that had met with the Governor.

786
01:35:09,000 --> 01:35:12,000
And they had a discussion.

787
01:35:12,000 --> 01:35:15,000
And the other discussion was constitutionally.

788
01:35:15,000 --> 01:35:22,000
If he called the session constitutionally, we got to convene.

789
01:35:22,000 --> 01:35:27,000
But the consensus was, among them, we don't have to do anything.

790
01:35:27,000 --> 01:35:36,000
So finally, Mr. Speaker said to me, Mr. Chairman, you might have saw it over there.

791
01:35:36,000 --> 01:35:39,000
What do you got to say about this?

792
01:35:40,000 --> 01:35:42,000
I said, Mr. President, I'm talking about the newman.

793
01:35:42,000 --> 01:35:49,000
Mr. Speaker, I serve at your will in pleasure.

794
01:35:49,000 --> 01:36:05,000
And if you have not removed me when the Governor calls a space association, I'm going to do everything I can to get a bill out of that house, out of the committee and get a pass.

795
01:36:05,000 --> 01:36:07,000
And I turned to the Lieutenant Governor.

796
01:36:07,000 --> 01:36:13,000
I said, Mr. Governor, and she goes, look, might have paid if I sent a bill over there.

797
01:36:13,000 --> 01:36:22,000
And if they know about it over there, but the news media and impede chairs.

798
01:36:22,000 --> 01:36:24,000
So that was it.

799
01:36:24,000 --> 01:36:27,000
And he did not remove me.

800
01:36:28,000 --> 01:36:36,000
And as the bill, that was a section of the bill of what I didn't want in the taxes.

801
01:36:36,000 --> 01:36:37,000
All right.

802
01:36:37,000 --> 01:36:46,000
And then after bills passed both houses, we met in the education committee room.

803
01:36:46,000 --> 01:36:48,000
That's the conference committee.

804
01:36:49,000 --> 01:36:58,000
If you meet on the Senate side, the chairman of Senate Education Committee chair for the House chair chair.

805
01:36:58,000 --> 01:37:02,000
So I was chairing the conference committee room, not meeting.

806
01:37:02,000 --> 01:37:04,000
I call it the order.

807
01:37:04,000 --> 01:37:11,000
So some of the Ellis Bowdron, blind son, but some others he could be.

808
01:37:11,000 --> 01:37:13,000
You know who he is.

